    <statement><p>Calculate the following. Use an improper fraction in your answer.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{4}{ \frac{2}{5} - \frac{2}{3} } =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-15</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify a complex fraction, we find the common denominator of all fractions. In this case, it is <m>15</m>. We multiply the complex fraction<rsq/>s numerator and denominator by this common denominator, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{4}{ \frac{2}{5} - \frac{2}{3} } 
      \amp = \frac{4 \cdot 15}{ (\frac{2}{5}-\frac{2}{3}) \cdot 15 } \\
      \amp = \frac{60}{ \frac{2}{5} \cdot 15 - \frac{2}{3} \cdot 15 } \\
      \amp = \frac{60}{ 6  - 10 } \\
      \amp = \frac{60}{-4} \\
      \amp = {-15}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Here is a simple way to do fraction multiplication:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \frac{2}{5} \cdot 15 = 15 \div 5 \cdot 2 = 6 }</m></p>
</solution>
